{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.08,0.13,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52112"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4093"},{"type":"tags","id":"11116"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a six-month history of worsening chronic pelvic pain and dysmenorrhoea. Her symptoms are affecting her quality of life and work attendance. She has regular heavy periods lasting seven days. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with a regular partner and is not currently trying to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals tenderness in the left iliac fossa without guarding. Bimanual examination reveals a tender left adnexal mass. Transvaginal ultrasound shows a 4 cm left ovarian cyst with ground glass appearance. Her CA-125 is 65 kU/L (0-35).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic cystectomy","Expectant management with analgesia","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Intrauterine device with levonorgestrel","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic pelvic pain, dysmenorrhoea, and an ovarian cyst with ultrasound features suggestive of an endometrioma. The elevated CA-125 supports but does not confirm the diagnosis of endometriosis. Given the presence of a sizeable endometrioma and significant symptoms, surgical management is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Early surgical intervention can prevent disease progression, preserve ovarian tissue, and provide definitive diagnosis through histology. Surgery also allows assessment of the extent of endometriosis and treatment of other endometriotic deposits if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E may provide symptom relief but will not address the underlying endometrioma. Medical management alone may allow the endometrioma to enlarge and cause further ovarian damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management with analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate given the severity of symptoms affecting quality of life and the presence of an endometrioma. This approach may allow progression of disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist\u003C/strong\u003E therapy causes a hypoestrogenic state and significant side effects including bone mineral density loss. It will not resolve the endometrioma and is typically reserved for cases refractory to surgical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrauterine device with levonorgestrel\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for endometriosis symptoms but will not address the endometrioma. It is usually considered as an option for preventing recurrence after surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early surgical management of endometriomas is recommended to prevent disease progression and preserve fertility.","Ground glass appearance on transvaginal ultrasound is characteristic of endometriomas.","CA-125 may be elevated in endometriosis but has limited diagnostic value."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Endometriosis: Clinical Practice Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Endometriosis-Clinical-Practice-Guideline.pdf","Tsamantioti ES, Mahdy H. Endometriosis. [Updated 2023 Jan 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK567777/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52112"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52112"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T18:06:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T18:06:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"ques